  "chunk_index": 33,
  "summary": "Hercule Poirot confronts Alastair Blunt, revealing that he has discovered the marriage certificate between Blunt and Gerta Grant. Poirot explains that Frank Carter witnessed Blunt leaving Morley's office and notes that the condition of Morley's body proves the murderer, rather than Morley himself, was the one who saw Amberloch's teeth. Poirot also reveals that the real Helen Montresor died years ago in Canada, and that Blunt had been exploiting her identity.\n\nBlunt admits to the deception, explaining that he and Gerta Grant maintained a secret, \"royal\" marriage through various roles and aliases to avoid social scrutiny and maintain their mutual attraction. Blunt confesses to the murders of Mabel Sainsbury-West, Amberloch, and Morley, as well as the death of Lady Chatterley. He admits to killing Mabel by drugging her tea with barbiturates and killing Amberloch using his dental tools. Blunt justifies these murders by claiming he is a vital figure for the stability and democracy of England, arguing that his reputation must be protected to prevent national ruin and that the victims' lives were insignificant compared to his service to the country.\n\nPoirot rejects this utilitarian logic, accusing Blunt of being driven by an excessive love for power. Poirot refuses Blunt's suggestion to withdraw from the case and instead has him arrested. Following the arrest, Poirot informs Jane Olivia and Howard Rees that the matter is over. As Poirot walks home, he discusses the case with Mr. Barnes, reflecting on the moral implications of Blunt's actions. The encounter ends with a shock when Mr. Barnes reveals that he is actually Albert Chatman, leaving Poirot in stunned silence.",
